ys, and memoirs, this book recreates the context for the volunteers’ actions. It explores how the upper classes used the strike to assert their ideological right to define Britishness as well as how scholars, novelists, playwrights, diarists, museum curators, local historians, and even a theme restaurant, have continued to recycle the strike to define British identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSocial classeszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  a1926 General Strike.  aBritishness.  aclass divisions.  ahumour.  anational community.  anational folk symbols.  apostwar society.  asocial status.  asocio-economic status.  aspeech.  avolunteering.1 aSaltzman, Rachelle Hope, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130655423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130655/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles